=========================================
C++ unordered_multimap – Interview Notes
=========================================

1. What is unordered_multimap?
------------------------------
unordered_multimap is an unordered associative container that stores
multiple key-value pairs with the same key.

Implemented using:
- Hash Table

Header:
#include <unordered_map>

Syntax:
unordered_multimap<int, string> umm;

----------------------------------------

2. Properties
-------------
✓ Stores key-value pairs
✓ Duplicate keys are allowed
✓ Keys are NOT sorted
✓ Values are NOT sorted
✓ Average O(1) insertion/search/deletion
✓ Worst case O(n) (hash collisions)

Example:
Key   Value
10    A
10    B
20    C
30    D

----------------------------------------

3. Example
----------

#include <iostream>
#include <unordered_map>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    unordered_multimap<int, string> umm;

    umm.insert({1, "Apple"});
    umm.insert({2, "Banana"});
    umm.insert({1, "Mango"});
    umm.insert({3, "Orange"});

    for(auto &p : umm)
        cout << p.first << " -> " << p.second << endl;
}

Possible Output:
1 -> Apple
3 -> Orange
1 -> Mango
2 -> Banana

(Output order is NOT guaranteed.)

----------------------------------------

4. Common Functions
-------------------

insert()

umm.insert({1, "Apple"});

emplace()

umm.emplace(2, "Banana");

find()

auto it = umm.find(1);

Returns iterator to ONE element with key 1.

count()

cout << umm.count(1);

Returns number of elements having key 1.

equal_range()

auto range = umm.equal_range(1);

Returns iterators to ALL elements with key 1.

erase(key)

umm.erase(1);

Removes ALL elements with key 1.

erase(iterator)

auto it = umm.find(1);
if(it != umm.end())
    umm.erase(it);

Removes only ONE element.

size()

umm.size();

empty()

umm.empty();

clear()

umm.clear();

----------------------------------------

5. Iterating over all elements
------------------------------

for(auto &p : umm)
{
    cout << p.first << " "
         << p.second << endl;
}

----------------------------------------

6. Iterating over duplicate keys
--------------------------------

auto range = umm.equal_range(1);

for(auto it = range.first;
    it != range.second;
    ++it)
{
    cout << it->first
         << " "
         << it->second << endl;
}

